<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="329" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1142,1421]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,598,1142,1168]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Material examined. TAN 0102/K0809</emphasis>
, a few stems up to 
<quantity box="[815,894,1143,1169]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
high, with putative male gonothecae, on tube of benthic organism (
<collectionCode box="[358,432,1179,1205]" country="New Zealand" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/nyq3-3g6s" name="National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research" pageId="8" pageNumber="329" type="Other institutional type">NIWA</collectionCode>
144358).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1142,1421]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,482,1214,1241]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Measurements (in µm).</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[492,623,1215,1241]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Hydrotheca</emphasis>
: diameter at aperture 190–200, diameter at diaphragm 125, height 50. 
<emphasis box="[151,286,1251,1277]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Hydrophore</emphasis>
: adcauline length 300.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="329" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1142,1421]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1287,1313]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Remarks.</emphasis>
The relatively long hydrophore and the shape and size of the hydrotheca allow a certain identification. It is worth mentioning the occasional presence of a pseudodiaphragm, faintly visible in stained material (
<figureCitation box="[1326,1415,1323,1349]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,187,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[241,1345,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Symplectoscyphus cumberlandicus (Jäderholm, 1905): A, hydrothecae; B, gonotheca. Halecium exaggeratum Peña Cantero, Boero &amp; Piraino, 2013: C, distal part of internode with hydrophore (arrow pointing to pseudodiaphragm) and hydrotheca. Schizotricha falcata Peña Cantero, 1998: D, forked hydrocladial internode and ahydrothecate internode (arrow); E, unforked hydrocladial internode showing hydrotheca and nematothecae; F, gonotheca; G–H, forked hydrocladial internodes from holotype (arrows pointing to perisarc indentations). Scale bar: 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736697/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="329" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1142,1421]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,512,1358,1385]" pageId="8" pageNumber="329">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
The material, which represents the first record from the Balleny Islands, was collected at a depth of 
<quantity box="[405,478,1395,1421]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.92" pageId="8" pageNumber="329" unit="m" value="292.0">292 m</quantity>
, off Young Island. Gonothecae present in March.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
